/ph> is called.","pos":[13842,14036],"source":" This means that when you invoke the <xref:System.Windows.Media.VisualTreeHelper.HitTest%2A> method, your overridden implementation of <xref:System.Windows.Media.Visual.HitTestCore%2A> is called."},{"content":"Your overridden method is called when a hit test falls within the bounding rectangle of the visual object, even if the coordinate falls outside the rendered content of the visual object.","pos":[14037,14223]},{"content":"There may be times when you want to hit test against both the bounding rectangle and the rendered content of a visual object.","pos":[14499,14624]},{"content":"By using the <ph id=\"ph1\">`PointHitTestParameters`</ph> parameter value in your overridden <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Visual.HitTestCore%2A&gt;</ph> method as the parameter to the base method <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Visual.HitTestCore%2A&gt;</ph>, you can perform actions based on a hit of the bounding rectangle of a visual object, and then perform a second hit test against the rendered content of the visual object.","pos":[14625,15012],"source":" By using the `PointHitTestParameters` parameter value in your overridden <xref:System.Windows.Media.Visual.HitTestCore%2A> method as the parameter to the base method <xref:System.Windows.Media.Visual.HitTestCore%2A>, you can perform actions based on a hit of the bounding rectangle of a visual object, and then perform a second hit test against the rendered content of the visual object."},{"pos":[15290,15298],"content":"See also","linkify":"See also","nodes":[{"content":"See also","pos":[0,8]}]},{"pos":[15562,15648],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Hit Test Using DrawingVisuals Sample<ept id=\"p1\">](https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=159994)</ept>","source":"[Hit Test Using DrawingVisuals Sample](https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=159994)"},{"pos":[15651,15742],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Hit Test with Win32 Interoperation Sample<ept id=\"p1\">